docs.snippet: New York City in 1975 was experiencing perhaps the worst moment in its history. The photographer Meryl Meisler loved it immediately.

headline.print_headline: A Dirty, Broke and Wonderful New York
headline.main: A Photographer’s Search for Joy in Uncertain Times

docs.snippet: A British man received a suspended one-year sentence Tuesday from a Cambodian court that found him guilty of producing pornography by posting photos on social media of sexually suggestive dancing at a party with other foreigners.

headline.print_headline: Briton in Cambodian Wild Party Case Given Suspended Sentence
headline.main: Briton in Cambodian Wild Party Case Given Suspended Sentence

docs.snippet: France expects the European Union to obtain a full exemption from new U.S. tariffs on aluminium and steel that are due to kick in on March 23, the French finance minister Bruno Le Maire said on Monday after meeting his U.S. counterpart.

headline.print_headline: France Expects EU to Get Full Exemption From U.S. Tariffs-Le Maire
headline.main: France Expects EU to Get Full Exemption From U.S. Tariffs-Le Maire

docs.snippet: Your daily look at late-breaking news, upcoming events and the stories that will be talked about Monday:
The team behind the P.T. Barnum musical answered reader questions about the word-of-mouth hit. Even they were a little surprised by moviegoers’ responses.

headline.print_headline: Hugh Jackman and Company on Fans of ‘The Greatest Showman’
headline.main: Hugh Jackman and Company on Fans of ‘The Greatest Showman’

docs.snippet: U.S. media company Meredith Corp said on Wednesday it cut about 200 jobs and would lay off another 1,000 as it streamlines its operations following the completion of its Time Inc acquisition.

headline.print_headline: Meredith to Cut About 1,200 Jobs, Sell Some Time Publications
headline.main: Meredith to Cut About 1,200 Jobs, Sell Some Time Publications

docs.snippet: Ukraine's plans to force activists and non-governmental organizations to declare detailed financial information are likely to have a chilling effect on civil society, two leading international rights bodies said on Friday.

headline.print_headline: Ukraine NGO Laws Risk 'Chilling Effect' on Civil Society: Rights Bodies
headline.main: Ukraine NGO Laws Risk 'Chilling Effect' on Civil Society: Rights Bodies

docs.snippet: Newer versions of Google’s browser include a setting to easily mute web pages that would otherwise open with audio blaring.

headline.print_headline: How to Shut Up Noisy Sites in Chrome
headline.main: How to Shut Up Noisy Sites in Chrome

docs.snippet: Oil prices edged up on Tuesday, lifted by tensions in the Middle East, although rising output in the United States and shaky stock markets put a lid on further gains.

headline.print_headline: Oil Prices Rise on Middle East Tension, but Soaring U.S. Output Caps Gains
headline.main: Oil Prices Rise on Middle East Tension, but Soaring U.S. Output Caps Gains

docs.snippet: Qatar's government communications office has filed a U.S. lawsuit against people who it said are conducting an illegal social media and internet campaign to spread false information and hurt the country's businesses.

headline.print_headline: Qatar Sues Online Critics of Its Government: U.S. Lawsuit
headline.main: Qatar Sues Online Critics of Its Government: U.S. Lawsuit
